  "source": "Theorem:\ngiven: a, b, c, d is \\set\nthen: \\set.theoretic.ordered.pair:of{a}:and{b} = \\set.theoretic.ordered.pair:of{c}:and{d}\niff:\n. a = c\n. b = d\nDocumented:\n. description: \"Two ordered pairs are equal if and only if their first coordinates are equal and their second coordinates are equal. This justifies thinking of an ordered pair $(a, b)$ as having a first coordinate $a$ and a second coordinate $b$.\"\nId: \"6e4b61e7-24a6-4a40-9ac1-d288ce0ebf22\"",
